BILL NO. 36-0005
Thirty-Sixth Legislature of the Virgin Islands
February 27, 2025
An Act amending title 16 Virgin Islands Code, chapter 2, section 99 establishing a mandatory
minimum bail amount in domestic violence cases
PROPOSED BY: Senators Angel L. Bolques, Jr., Dwayne M. DeGraff and
Carla J. Joseph
1 Be it enacted by the Legislature of the Virgin Islands:
2 SECTION 1. (a) Title 16 Virgin Islands Code, chapter 2, section 99, is amended as
3 follows:
4 (1) subsection (b):
5 (A) in paragraphs (1), (2) and (3) by by striking “with no 10% provision”
6 and inserting “however, bail must be determined based on the defendant’s risk to
7 the victim and the community and fully secured where there is clear and convincing
8 evidence of a threat to the victim or likelihood of flight” after “harm;” in each
9 paragraph respectively; and
10 (B) by inserting the following paragraph (4):
11 “(4) If the underlying crime has a higher bail amount than the amount
12 in subsection (b) of this section, the higher bail amount shall apply.”

2
1 (b) subsection (c) is amended by inserting the following after “forthwith.”: “If the
2 People can prove by clear and convincing evidence that the defendant contacted the victim in
3 violation of a protective order, the defendant shall be remanded to custody and bail shall be
4 reconsidered based on the severity of the violation. The court may consider alternative non-
5 monetary conditions, such as electronic monitoring, house arrest, or mandatory check-ins
6 where the defendant demonstrates financial hardship, provided these measures sufficiently
7 protect the victim. The court shall also consider risk assessments, victim statements, and law
8 enforcement recommendations when setting bail or release conditions to ensure protection of
9 victims while upholding constitutional protections. To be released, the defendant must
10 demonstrate to the Court that he is not a danger to the victim.”
11 (c) subsection (e) is amended by inserting the following after “center.”: “Appropriate
12 treatment options include a certified Partner Abuse Intervention Program.” The court may
13 require the defendant to complete a domestic violence intervention program from a court
14 approved provider.
15 BILL SUMMARY
16 This bill establishes a mandatory minimum bail amount for a person arrested for or
17 charged with a crime that constitutes domestic violence.
